## 📌 Arrays vs Lists
| Feature | Arrays | List Interface |
|---------|--------|----------------|
| Size | Fixed | Dynamic |
| Performance | Faster (primitive storage) | Flexible, but overhead |
| Methods | Limited (`Arrays` utility class) | Rich API |
| Use Case | Low-level, performance critical | High-level, flexible collections |

---

## 📌 Advanced Use Cases
- **Multidimensional Arrays**: `int[][] matrix = new int[3][3];`  
- **Collections Utility**: `Collections.sort(list)` vs `Arrays.sort(arr)`  
- **Streams**: `list.stream().filter(...).collect(...)`  
- **Conversion**:  
  - Array → List: `Arrays.asList(arr)`  
  - List → Array: `list.toArray(new String[0])`  

---

✅ **Tip for Interviews**:  
- Arrays are best for **fixed-size, performance-critical** tasks.  
- Lists are best for **dynamic, flexible** data structures.  
- Know **time complexities**:  
  - Array access/update → O(1)  
  - ArrayList add/remove (end) → O(1) amortized  
  - LinkedList add/remove → O(1) at ends, O(n) at index  
